<b><it>Comfort and Joy</it></b> is a soundtrack album by <person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<artist wordnetid="109812338" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../158/199158.xml">
Mark Knopfler</link></artist>
</person>
 for the 1984 <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../794/2467794.xml">
film of the same name</link>, written and directed by <physical_entity wordnetid="100001930" confidence="0.8">
<communicator wordnetid="109610660" confidence="0.8">
<person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.8">
<leader wordnetid="109623038" confidence="0.8">
<administrator wordnetid="109770949" confidence="0.8">
<screenwriter wordnetid="110564400" confidence="0.8">
<causal_agent wordnetid="100007347" confidence="0.8">
<scriptwriter wordnetid="110564905" confidence="0.8">
<writer wordnetid="110794014" confidence="0.8">
<head wordnetid="110162991" confidence="0.8">
<director wordnetid="110014939" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../449/1353449.xml">
Bill Forsyth</link></director>
</head>
</writer>
</scriptwriter>
</causal_agent>
</screenwriter>
</administrator>
</leader>
</person>
</communicator>
</physical_entity>
 and starring <person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<actor wordnetid="109765278" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../968/1560968.xml">
Bill Paterson</link></actor>
</person>
.<p>

Although there were only three original pieces written for the movie, addition songs from the Dire Straits’ album "<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../119/363119.xml">
Love Over Gold</link>" are used throughout the film. According to a review of the film by Philip Gillett, director Forsyth once admitted in an interview that he was “trying to mirror the tone” of the album by featuring the tracks “<song wordnetid="107048000" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../768/5446768.xml">
Telegraph Road</link></song>
” and “<music wordnetid="107020895" confidence="0.8">
<song wordnetid="107048000" confidence="0.8">
<auditory_communication wordnetid="107109019" confidence="0.8">
<musical_composition wordnetid="107037465" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../190/6129190.xml">
Private Investigations</link></musical_composition>
</auditory_communication>
</song>
</music>
.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%221%22])">1</ref>  Dialogue in the movie also makes reference to the band and song lyrics. After the main character's car has been vandalized a colleague says "I hear the seven deadly sins and the terrible twins came to call on you", a direct quote from the song "<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../119/363119.xml">
It Never Rains</link>".</p>
<p>

The score was only ever released as a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../121/172121.xml">
45rpm</link> 12" <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../121/172121.xml">
vinyl record</link>,<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%222%22])">2</ref> and is therefore quite rare. </p>

